### Polish Science Day
##font-size:80%## Source: <https://certyfikatpolski.pl/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/4-5.02.2024-B1_arkusz_egzaminacyjny.pdf#page=11>

<small>~Text with gaps~</small>
Polish Science Day is one of the youngest national holidays in the Polish calendar. It was first celebrated in 2021. Its goal is to recognize the most outstanding Polish scientists, encourage young people to explore the world, and show them that science can be fascinating. These activities are intended to motivate students to pursue scientific careers. The birthday of Polish astronomer {{<img src=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f2/Nikolaus_Kopernikus.jpg>|[Nicolaus Copernicus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicolaus_Copernicus)}}, February 19th, was chosen as Polish Science Day because he was one of our most distinguished scientists. Nowadays, simple scientific research is accessible to everyone – even small children can have telescopes or microscopes and conduct observations. For young children, it's a passion that can turn into an interesting profession. Polish Science Day is a holiday that should be especially celebrated in schools and universities. Students can, for example, prepare presentations about scientists. A lesson at a museum is also an interesting idea. Companies or businesses that use scientific discoveries and can share these with young people should join in celebrating this day.

